The most basic command for creating a table in LaTeX is `\begin{table}`, which creates a new table environment. The optional argument to this command specifies the width of the table, e.g., `\begin{table}[1\textwidth]`. You can then insert your table content using standard LaTeX syntax.

To change the properties of a table, you can use the `\makecell` command, which takes two arguments: the first is the contents of the first row, and the second is the contents of the second row, where each row is split into two cells using the delimiter character specified as the third argument, e.g., `\makecell{Header & Header \\ 1 & 2 \\ 3 & 4 \\ 5 & 6}`. We can use the optional fourth argument to specify a different delimiter for the second row, e.g., `\makecell{Header & Header & \\ 1 & 2 & \\ 3 & 4 & \\ 5 & 6 &}`. To adjust the size of the table, you can use the \begin{code}
\resizebox{\textwidth}{!}{<content>}
\end{code} command, where \begin{code}
<content>
\end{code} is the table content. To adjust the alignment, spacing, and borders of the table, you can use the \begin{code}
\begin{tabular}{<specifications>}
\end{code} command, where \begin{code}
<specifications>
\end{code} is a list of key-value pairs representing the properties of each row. For example, to align the text in the first column to the left and the text in the second column to the center, you can use \begin{code}
\begin{tabular}{>{\raggedleft}p{0.25\textwidth} >{\centering}p{0.75\textwidth}}
\end{code}.

To create a table with three columns and four rows, you can use the following code:

\begin{code}
\begin{table}[1\textwidth]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{>{\raggedleft}p{0.25\textwidth}>{\centering}p{0.75\textwidth}}
Header & Header & 1 & 2 \\
3 & 4 & 5 & 6
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
